## 6. Organizational Philosophy

**RISK-001-REQ-6.1 (Single classification):** Every unit of work belongs to exactly one Risk Class at any given time. A unit of work MUST NOT be simultaneously governed by two different Risk Classes' floors.

**RISK-001-REQ-6.2 (Highest applicable governs):** Where a unit of work could plausibly be classified under more than one Risk Class's criteria (§8), its effective Risk Class is the **highest** applicable classification, without exception. This applies before any manual override is considered (§9).

**RISK-001-REQ-6.3 (Risk ≠ priority, strict separation):** Risk Class MUST NOT be used, by any role, as an input to scheduling, sequencing, or prioritization decisions. PM-SPEC's Decision Rights over scheduling (PM-SPEC §3) are unaffected by a unit of work's Risk Class; a high-risk item is not thereby high-priority, and a low-risk item is not thereby low-priority. The two concepts are computed and consumed independently, even though both may appear in the same work-item record.

**RISK-001-REQ-6.4 (Determinism as a goal, not a guarantee):** Risk classification SHOULD be deterministic wherever the applicable criteria can be reduced to checkable properties of the unit of work (e.g., "touches broker integration code" is checkable; "feels risky" is not). Where full determinism is not yet achievable (§14 Bootstrap Behavior), classification MUST still follow the same fixed criteria applied consistently, even if applied manually.

**RISK-001-REQ-6.5 (Floor, never ceiling, for humans):** No human or AI role may manually assign a Risk Class lower than the deterministic minimum computed from a unit of work's declared properties. Manual action may only raise the effective classification (§9).

