## 8. Risk Classes

**RISK-001-REQ-8.1:** The organization recognizes exactly six Risk Classes, R0 through R5, in strictly increasing order of governance floor. No work item may be assigned a Risk Class outside this set, and no seventh class may be introduced except as a `MAJOR` amendment to this standard (§24).

| Class | Name | Representative Examples | Direct Effect on Production Financial Behavior or Constitutional Governance? |
|---|---|---|---|
| **R0** | Administrative | Formatting, documentation, meeting notes, planning, roadmap cleanup | No |
| **R1** | Internal Engineering | Tooling, internal scripts, refactoring, generated documentation, developer experience | No |
| **R2** | Technical Change | APIs, schemas, infrastructure, architecture, internal technical behavior with no direct effect on approved trading or organizational policy | No |
| **R3** | Protected Technical | Broker integrations, authentication, security, strategy implementation, market-data interpretation, recommendation logic, production financial behavior | Yes — technical/financial |
| **R4** | Organizational Governance | RES documents, RoleSpecs, POS requirements, governance rules, approval rules, interaction standards, execution profiles, authority definitions | Yes — governance |
| **R5** | Constitutional | Constitutional philosophy, authority hierarchy, human authority, canonical truth model, organizational operating model, foundational governance | Yes — foundational |

**RISK-001-REQ-8.2:** These classes and their examples are illustrative anchors, not an exhaustive enumeration. A unit of work not obviously matching a listed example MUST still be classified by matching the closest applicable *criterion* (the column definitions and the qualitative description), not left unclassified pending a future update to the examples list.

**RISK-001-REQ-8.3:** This standard, and the RES-001/RES-002/POS-RS corpus, are themselves R4 (Organizational Governance) artifacts, except for statements of foundational authority or canonical-truth philosophy, which are R5 (Constitutional). A change to this standard's governance-floor tables (§10) is R4; a change to §6 (Organizational Philosophy) or §1 (Purpose) touching the risk-vs-priority separation itself is R5, as it alters foundational operating model, not merely a rule within it.

