## 9. Deterministic Classification and Multiple-Class Resolution

**RISK-001-REQ-9.1:** Deterministic classification is computed by evaluating a unit of work against the criteria in §8's table (and any future POS-encoded rule set, §16) and selecting the single highest-matching class per §6.2.

**RISK-001-REQ-9.2:** Where a unit of work's declared properties match criteria in more than one Risk Class (e.g., a change that is both an internal refactor (R1) and touches broker-integration code (R3)), the effective Risk Class MUST be the highest match (R3 in this example), computed before considering any manual override.

**RISK-001-REQ-9.3:** A unit of work's properties used for classification (what artifacts it touches, what systems it affects) MUST be declared explicitly as part of the work item, not inferred silently by the classifying role. An undeclared property that would have raised the classification, if later discovered, requires immediate reclassification and, if governance already proceeded under the lower class, an incident record (POS-RS §7.7).

**RISK-001-REQ-9.4:** Reclassification upward at any point MUST immediately apply that class's full governance floor to any remaining ungoverned steps; it does not retroactively invalidate governance steps already correctly completed under the lower class, but any step still pending MUST be re-evaluated against the new floor.

### 9.1 Manual Override Rules

**RISK-001-REQ-9.1.1:** Any role holding CONSULT or higher authority (RES-002 §8.1) over a unit of work MAY manually raise its effective Risk Class above the deterministic minimum, with a stated rationale recorded as a POS decision record (POS-RS §7.6).

**RISK-001-REQ-9.1.2:** No role, including the Founder, may manually lower a unit of work's effective Risk Class below its deterministic minimum. This is an absolute constraint, not a tiered authority right — it is not subject to any DECIDE/RECOMMEND tier, because it is not a decision this standard grants to any role (RES-002 §8.3's default-deny principle applies: an action not explicitly granted is denied, and lowering below the deterministic floor is never explicitly granted).

**RISK-001-REQ-9.1.3:** A manual override raising classification MUST be logged with the specific rationale and remains in effect for the life of the unit of work unless a subsequent, separately-justified override further raises it. Overrides are never silently reverted to the deterministic minimum.

