## 11. Approval Requirements (Elaboration)

**RISK-001-REQ-11.1:** "Approval" in §10.1 means the specific authority named in that row has recorded a POS decision record (POS-RS §7.6) with status `approved` before the unit of work may proceed to merge/deployment.

**RISK-001-REQ-11.2:** Approval MUST NOT be inferred from silence, delay, or the absence of an objection. An explicit `approved` record is required at R2 and above; R0/R1 MAY rely on implicit self-approval per §10.1.

**RISK-001-REQ-11.3:** Approval authority named in §10.1 is a floor, not a ceiling: a RoleSpec MAY require additional approvals (e.g., a specific role's RoleSpec requiring its own sign-off), but MUST NOT substitute a lower-tier approver for the one named here.

**RISK-001-REQ-11.4 (Constitutional Review, R5 only):** For R5 units of work, "Constitutional Review" means an explicit, separately-recorded check that the change does not silently alter human authority, the canonical-truth model, or the fixed authority hierarchy (RES-001 §4) without those specific changes being the stated subject of the amendment. This is a distinct check from Structural Review (RES-002 §20) and MUST be recorded separately.

---

## 12. Independent Review Requirements (Elaboration)

**RISK-001-REQ-12.1:** Independent Review, wherever required by §10.1 (R3 and above), follows the mechanics defined in RES-002 §13.1 and produces a POS review record per POS-RS §7.11. This standard adds no new review mechanism; it only determines the classes at which review is mandatory versus optional.

**RISK-001-REQ-12.2:** The Independent Review instance for an R3+ unit of work MUST NOT be the same instance (or role, where a role would otherwise be permitted to self-review at lower classes) that authored or assigned the work, consistent with RES-002 §13.1's assignment/acceptance separation.

---

## 13. Verification and Evidence Expectations (Elaboration)

**RISK-001-REQ-13.1:** "Verification" is the act of checking evidence against acceptance criteria; "evidence" is the artifact being checked. §10.1 fixes the minimum evidence type and verifying party per class; this standard does not define what constitutes technically sufficient evidence content for a given change — that is ARCH-SPEC's acceptance-criteria domain (ARCH-SPEC §6).

**RISK-001-REQ-13.2:** Evidence for R3+ units of work MUST be typed per POS-RS §15.1 (e.g., `test_result`, `dry_run_output`, `data_citation`) so that Automation can validate evidence-type-appropriateness before the unit of work is marked review-ready (POS-RS §10.3).

---

## 14. Merge/Deployment Implications (Elaboration)

**RISK-001-REQ-14.1:** Merge authority and deployment authority in §10.1 are independent of technical readiness certification: Architect certification of technical readiness (ARCH-SPEC §3) is necessary but never sufficient at R2 and above; the named approver in §10.1 must additionally act.

**RISK-001-REQ-14.2:** No unit of work may be deployed to a production system carrying financial or governance consequence (R3–R5) without a rollback plan meeting the §10.1 row's expectation existing and being reviewed before deployment, not drafted retroactively after an incident.

---

## 15. Escalation Rules (Elaboration)

**RISK-001-REQ-15.1:** Escalation triggered by ambiguity in Risk Class assignment itself (i.e., a role is unsure which class applies) is always resolved upward: when in doubt, classify at the higher candidate class and escalate the ambiguity for confirmation, never proceed at the lower class pending resolution.

**RISK-001-REQ-15.2:** Escalation postures in §10.1 govern *whether* a default-forward path (RES-002 §16.3) is permitted for CONSULT relationships tied to a unit of work; at R4–R5, no default-forward path is permitted regardless of what an individual RoleSpec's §16.3 provision might otherwise allow — this standard's stricter rule controls per §5.1.

---

## 16. Relationship to the POS

**RISK-001-REQ-16.1:** The POS is the canonical system of record for every unit of work's declared properties, deterministic classification result, any manual overrides with rationale, and the full governance-dimension satisfaction state (§10.1) at any point in time.

**RISK-001-REQ-16.2:** The POS MUST prevent (or, where not yet technically enforceable, detect and flag, per POS-RS §16.2's enforcement/detection distinction) any attempt to advance a unit of work past a governance dimension's floor without the required record existing.

**RISK-001-REQ-16.3:** The POS MUST retain full history of classification, override, and governance-satisfaction events per unit of work, immutably, consistent with POS-RS §8.1 (Auditability).

---

## 17. Automation Expectations

**RISK-001-REQ-17.1:** The POS SHOULD (Recommendation, escalating to Requirement once technically implemented per §18 Bootstrap Behavior) compute deterministic Risk Class automatically from a unit of work's declared properties, applying §8's criteria and §6.2's highest-applicable rule without human judgment, whenever those properties are structurally declared (e.g., "this change touches file path X mapped to broker-integration scope").

**RISK-001-REQ-17.2:** Automation MAY compute and surface a deterministic classification but MUST NOT be granted authority to lower a classification below what a human override has set, nor to approve, merge, or deploy on the strength of its own classification alone — classification is deterministic bookkeeping (RES-001 §13.3); the governance actions it triggers remain role-held decisions.

**RISK-001-REQ-17.3:** Where Automation's computed classification and a role's manual assessment differ, the higher of the two governs (§6.2, §9.1.2), and the discrepancy MUST be logged, not silently resolved in favor of either source.

---

## 18. Failure Behavior

**RISK-001-REQ-18.1:** If a unit of work's Risk Class cannot be determined with confidence (neither deterministic rule nor manual assessment clearly applies), the default behavior is to classify at the higher of the plausible candidates (§15.1) and escalate for confirmation before any governance dimension is marked satisfied.

**RISK-001-REQ-18.2:** If a governance dimension's required record (approval, evidence, review) is missing or invalid at the moment a unit of work is proposed for merge or deployment, the unit of work MUST be blocked at that step; no dimension may be skipped and back-filled after the fact.

**RISK-001-REQ-18.3:** Discovery, after the fact, that a unit of work proceeded under an incorrect (too-low) classification is an incident (POS-RS §7.7), not merely a data-correction event: it MUST produce an incident record identifying what governance was missed and whether any consequence resulted, independent of whether the underlying work was otherwise correct.

---

## 19. Bootstrap Behavior (Before Automation Exists)

**RISK-001-REQ-19.1:** Before the POS implements automated deterministic classification (§17.1), every unit of work MUST still be classified manually against the fixed criteria in §8, by the role assigning or performing the work, with the classification and rationale recorded as a POS artifact exactly as if Automation had produced it.

**RISK-001-REQ-19.2:** Manual bootstrap-era classification is held to the same §6.4 determinism goal: two different roles presented with the same declared properties MUST be expected to reach the same classification. A recurring discrepancy between manual classifiers on similar work is itself a signal that §8's criteria need clarification (§24 Evolution Policy), not that manual judgment should be trusted over the written criteria.

**RISK-001-REQ-19.3:** Bootstrap-era manual classifications are not exempt from any governance dimension in §10.1; the absence of Automation reduces *who* computes the classification, never *what* governance floor results from it.

**RISK-001-REQ-19.4:** Once Automation is capable of deterministic classification for a given category of work, that category's manual classification step is retired for that category specifically (not organization-wide in one cut-over), and the transition itself is logged as a POS release record (POS-RS §7.9).

