## 20. Regression Expectations

**RISK-001-REQ-20.1:** This standard's classification criteria (§8) and governance table (§10.1) MUST be validated against a maintained set of representative scenarios (at minimum one per Risk Class, plus at least two multiple-class-resolution scenarios per §6.2 and one manual-override scenario per §9.1), analogous to RES-002 §21's regression discipline.

**RISK-001-REQ-20.2:** Any amendment to §8 or §10.1 MUST NOT be promoted (§24) without passing the existing regression scenario set or explicitly revising a scenario with stated rationale.

**RISK-001-REQ-20.3:** A regression scenario demonstrating the risk/priority independence property (§7) MUST be included: a case where a high-priority, low-risk item and a low-priority, high-risk item are both processed correctly according to their respective, independently-determined governance floors and schedules.

---

## 21. Versioning

**RISK-001-REQ-21.1:** This standard uses the semantic versioning scheme defined in RES-001 §10 and RES-002 §19: `MAJOR` for changes to Risk Class definitions (§8), governance-floor table cells (§10.1), or the risk/priority independence principle (§6–§7); `MINOR` for changes to elaboration sections (§11–§19) that do not alter a floor; `PATCH` for non-behavioral clarification.

**RISK-001-REQ-21.2:** Per RES-002 §19.2, version numbers for this standard are monotonic and non-reusable, enforced by the POS once available, and by manual discipline during bootstrap (§19).

---

## 22. Evolution Policy

**RISK-001-REQ-22.1:** This standard is an R4 artifact except where noted otherwise (§8.3); amendments follow the R4 governance floor defined in its own §10.1 table — meaning a change to this document requires Founder approval, Independent Review, and Structural Review, applied reflexively to itself.

**RISK-001-REQ-22.2:** A proposed change to §6 (Organizational Philosophy) affecting the risk/priority independence principle itself is classified R5 under this standard's own criteria (§8.3) and requires Constitutional Review (§11.4) in addition to the standard R4 floor.

**RISK-001-REQ-22.3:** Introducing a seventh Risk Class, or removing one of R0–R5, is a `MAJOR`, R5-classified change requiring the fullest governance floor this standard defines, since it alters the foundational classification model every other governance document depends on.

**RISK-001-REQ-22.4:** As with RES-002 §22.4, this standard's own evolution is subject to the same discipline it imposes on others: any revision is versioned, reviewed, and regression-tested against the current governance corpus before promotion to `active`.

---

## 23. Non-Goals

To prevent scope drift (a named risk in the assignment context), this standard explicitly does not:
- Define technical review checklists (ARCH-SPEC's domain).
- Define scheduling or sequencing rules (PM-SPEC's domain).
- Specify POS implementation details for automated classification (POS-RS governs requirements; a future POS technical design governs implementation, per POS-RS §23's requirements/implementation-suggestion distinction).
- Define cybersecurity controls, a software risk register, or trading-specific risk management — those may reference this standard's classes but are not defined by it.

